### Problem 3 — Why NOT just pass everything to a plain Groq LLM?

You're right to push back. Here's the honest comparison:

| Approach | Quality | Cost | Effort | Best for |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **A. Groq (POC)** | 60-70% | Free | Zero | Proving the architecture |
| **B. Groq llama-3.1-70b** | 75-80% | ~$0.001/query | Zero | Good demo quality |
| **C. LoRA fine-tune Llama-3.1-8B** | 80-90% | ~$50 one-time (NRP GPU) | Medium | **Best production tradeoff** |
| **D. vLLM on NRP (70B, no fine-tune)** | 80-85% | NRP credits | Low setup | Large-model quality |
| **E. AgriLLM (domain pre-trained)** | 90%+ | High | High | Ideal long-term |

**Recommended Tiered Strategy:**

```
Phase 1 (POC — now):
  Groq llama-3.1-8b-instant
  Role: ALL nodes (planner, worker, solver, summarizer)
  Why: Free, fast, proves the pipeline works
  Weakness: Hallucinates ag-specific details (spray intervals, exact thresholds)

Phase 2 (Better demo):
  Groq llama-3.1-70b-versatile as SOLVER only
  llama-3.1-8b-instant for planner/worker/summarizer
  Why: 70B is dramatically better for synthesis without costing much
  Cost: ~$0.001 per full query round-trip

Phase 3 (Production POC on NRP):
  vLLM serving Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct on NRP GPU pod
  + LoRA adapter fine-tuned on agricultural QA dataset:
    - USDA agricultural extension publications (open)
    - AgriQA benchmark dataset (GitHub)
    - Synthetic VINE-specific QA pairs (you generate these)
    - Iron Horse Vineyards field records (if available)
  Fine-tuning approach: QLoRA on 4x A100 (NRP has these)
  Result: A model that actually KNOWS ag thresholds, not retrieves them
```

**The key insight on fine-tuning:**
Fine-tuning doesn't replace RAG — they serve different purposes:

```
RAG (RAPTOR) answers:  "What is the current VWC threshold?"
Fine-tuned LLM knows:  "What does a VWC threshold MEAN for Pinot Noir in July?"
Together they produce:  Correct + contextualized recommendations
```

A fine-tuned model makes fewer hallucination errors on domain-specific numbers,
uses correct agronomic terminology, and generates better plans in the Planner node.

